<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xml:lang="en"><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.3.4">Jekyll</generator><link href="https://1917dc.github.io/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://1917dc.github.io/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" hreflang="en"/><updated>2024-12-01T22:31:13+00:00</updated><id>https://1917dc.github.io/feed.xml</id><title type="html">Earthmover</title><subtitle>A simple, whitespace theme for academics. Based on [*folio](https://github.com/bogoli/-folio) design. </subtitle><entry><title type="html">report</title><link href="https://1917dc.github.io/blog/2024/report/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="report"/><published>2024-11-29T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2024-11-29T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>https://1917dc.github.io/blog/2024/report</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://1917dc.github.io/blog/2024/report/"><![CDATA[<p>Hello, this is my first report on this blog.</p> <p>Today, I did two LeetCode exercises(easy exercises, but difficult to me), I’m really trying to focus on developing my problem-solving skills, mainly to apply on live code interviews for my internship oppotunities.</p> <p>I never did any LeetCode before, so those are my first experience in it. I plan to focus on deepening my understanding on data-structures and algorithms, which are the main pillars of computer science. I feel that the more I study those patterns, the more my understanding on problem-solving improve, so I’ll try to grind at least 1-2 exercise per day.</p> <h2 id="first-problem-palindrome-number"><span style="color: crimson">First problem: Palindrome number</span></h2> <p><strong>Given an integer x, return true if x is a palindrome, and false otherwise.</strong></p> <ul> <li>Follow up: Could you solve it without converting the integer to a string?</li> </ul> <h3 id="solution">Solution:</h3> <p>This is not the fastest way, but I did it without converting the number to a string, like the exercise told me to.</p> <p>It solves in O(n) time complexity.</p> <div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">class</span> <span class="nc">Solution</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">isPalindrome</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">int</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">-&gt;</span> <span class="nb">bool</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">reverse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
        <span class="n">temp</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">x</span>

        <span class="k">while</span> <span class="n">temp</span> <span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">last</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">temp</span> <span class="o">%</span> <span class="mi">10</span>
            <span class="n">reverse</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">reverse</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">last</span>
            <span class="n">temp</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">temp</span><span class="o">//</span><span class="mi">10</span>

        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">reverse</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="k">return</span> <span class="bp">True</span>
        <span class="k">return</span>  <span class="bp">False</span>
</code></pre></div></div> <h2 id="second-problem-roman-to-integer"><span style="color: crimson">Second problem: Roman to integer</span></h2> <p><strong>Given a roman numeral, convert it to an integer.</strong></p> <h3 id="solution-1">Solution:</h3> <p>This is the most intuitive way that I’ve thought of to solve this problem, not bad at all because it solves in O(n) time complexity.</p> <div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">class</span> <span class="nc">Solution</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">romanToInt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">self</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">s</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">-&gt;</span> <span class="nb">int</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">nums</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">I</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">V</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">X</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">L</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">50</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">C</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">D</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">500</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="s">M</span><span class="sh">'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">1000</span><span class="p">}</span>
        <span class="n">total</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>

        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nf">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nf">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">)):</span>
            <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="nf">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="ow">and</span> <span class="n">nums</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="n">nums</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]]:</span>
                <span class="n">total</span> <span class="o">-=</span> <span class="n">nums</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]]</span>
            <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
                <span class="n">total</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="n">nums</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]]</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">total</span>
</code></pre></div></div> <p>I’ve done fine today, did the things that I chalenged myself to, and I’m really proud of this. I have plans to study Machine Learning on next weeks, for further search of interships.</p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="report"/><category term="code"/><category term="leetcode"/><summary type="html"><![CDATA[progress report]]></summary></entry></feed>